This Actualite.cd report, published in the safety of Kinshasa, may also help to explain the silence of Radio Moto Butembo-Beni since 16 May 2019: Two journalists threatened with death by militia in eastern DR Congo.

I have been looking for other North Kivu-Ituri radio stations with websites and found none. A region with 10 million people has many radio and TV stations, but so far I've found only sites dead for years or no sites at all. Now I suspect that even those still operating are saying very little about Ebola or the response, rather than see their reporters killed and their stations burned down. - Mary Marshall]

- Wed 29 May 2019. Congo Ebola response must be elevated to maximum level, UN told
[The Guardian, abridged, edited]
< https://www.theguardian.com/global-development/2019/may/29/congo-ebola-response-must-be-elevated-to-maximum-level-un-told>

The UN has been urged by charities to ramp up Ebola prevention work in the Democratic Republic of the Congo to the highest level of emergency response.

Only 3 crises -- Yemen, Syria, and Mozambique -- are treated as the equivalent of a level-3 response, activated when agencies are unable to meet needs on the ground. Charities including Mercy Corps and Oxfam said the same declaration should also be made in DRC, following a recent acceleration in the spread of Ebola.

Almost 2000 cases of Ebola have been recorded since the outbreak began in August. As of [Mon 27 May 2019], 1287 people have died from the disease. Violence by armed groups and community mistrust have severely undermined attempts to halt the epidemic, forcing health workers to suspend vaccination and treatment work. Whitney Elmer, country director of DRC for Mercy Corps, said that declaring the equivalent of a level-three emergency would bring "manifold benefits" by clarifying the roles of agencies, allowing greater access to resources and attracting greater global attention. "There has never been an epidemic of this complexity or size in the DRC," said Elmer, adding that the crisis requires a new structure in line with its scale.

The global humanitarian coordination body, Inter-Agency Standing Committee, will consider the call when it meets on Wed. Among the factors to be considered are the scale and complexity of an epidemic, and the risk of a failure to respond effectively. A level-3 emergency, now known as a system-wide scale up, does not indicate the severity of the crisis, but is activated where there is a mismatch between need and agencies' ability to respond.

On [Tue 28 May 2019], Mike Ryan, assistant director-general of the World Health Organization's emergency preparedness and response programme, said progress had been made in fighting Ebola, including a drop in transmission of the disease in health facilities. But insecurity has continued to undermine the response, he added, repeatedly preventing work to identify and vaccinate people at risk of Ebola. There have been 174 attacks on health facilities so far this year [2019], a 3-fold increase compared with the period from August to December 2018.

In some areas, health workers are afraid to wear protective equipment because they fear they will be targeted by armed groups, according to WHO. Médecins sans Frontières warned it is "extremely worried" about the unpredictability of new cases.

--
