ProMED-mail rapporteur Mary Marshall

- Tue 28 May 2019. WHO experts say violence preventing end of Ebola outbreak
[CIDRAP (Center for Infectious Disease Research and Policy), edited]
http://www.cidrap.umn.edu/news-perspective/2019/05/who-experts-say-violence-preventing-end-ebola-outbreak
[byline: Stephanie Soucheray]

Today [28 May 2019] experts from WHO said the ongoing Ebola outbreak in the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC) is being fueled by violent security incidents. "The outbreak could be stopped ... but without a secure environment it's not possible," said Matshidiso Moeti, WHO regional director for Africa, in a teleconference today.

Violent incidents have tripled
------------------------------
The past 5 months have seen 174 attacks on health clinics and health workers, alike, Moeti said. The attacks have caused 5 deaths and 51 documented injuries. When compared with the first 5 months of the outbreak, which began last August [2018], that's a tripling of violence, she said. Over the weekend [25-26 May 2019], a community health worker near Mabalako was killed. The worker was trained to carry out response efforts in Vusahiro village. On the evening of the attack, 3 houses in the village were also burned.

The attacks are the sole reason the outbreak is not coming to an end, Moeti said, as each violent attack disrupts surveillance and vaccination efforts. "The technical means to stop this Ebola outbreak are available, but without access, they can't be employed optimally," Moeti said.

This week [week of 27 May 2019] David Gressly, MBA, who was appointed last week as the United Nation's Ebola czar, will create a new structure that could "crack the code" on violence, Moeti said. Gressly will arrive in Butembo tomorrow [29 May 2019], and one of his key objectives is healthcare worker security.

Over the weekend, the Ebola outbreak in North Kivu and Ituri provinces in the DRC grew by 26 cases, passing the 1900 case mark to a total of 1920 cases, according to the DRC yesterday [27 May 2019]. Among the 1920 cases are 1281 deaths and more than 500 survivors. As of yesterday, the DRC said 252 suspected cases are still under investigation, and 125 467 people had been vaccinated against the virus.

Nosocomial transmission drop; pop-up vaccination
------------------------------------------------
While violent attacks are on the rise, Mike Ryan, the WHO's executive director of emergency programs, highlighted some encouraging figures in the latest epidemiologic updates on the outbreak. "6 or 7 weeks ago, 35% of cases were nosocomial, meaning they contracted Ebola in the healthcare setting," said Ryan. "In the last 21 days that rate has dropped to 16% and in the last week, 5%." Ryan said the goal is zero nosocomial transmission. He also touted the effectiveness of "pop-up" vaccination clinics and community health teams that are working on a "zone-to-zone" level in active outbreak regions. "In Katwa, it's almost a cellular, street level of community engagement," Ryan said.

Katwa and Butembo are still the outbreak epicenters, and Ryan said the outbreak remains geographically contained. But even with certain wins, Ryan said he refused to speculate on the outbreak. "We may still see another wave of cases," he said.

MSF questions surveillance efforts
----------------------------------
Late last week [week of 20 May 2019], Doctors Without Borders (Médecins sans Frontières; MSF), which pulled out of the region in February [2019] because of violence, issued a statement on the outbreak, suggesting that surveillance is not effective. "More than 80% of new confirmed cases have not been identified as contacts. Additionally, as few as 32% of the new confirmed cases were linked back to known contacts. This means that the listing of contacts and surveillance are not effective," the statement said. "This also mean that while the number of new cases being reported is high, the real number is likely to be even higher."

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail rapporteur Mary Marshall

[It is very concerning that "more than 80% of new confirmed cases have not been identified as contacts." This means there are transmission chains that have not been identified. It will be very hard to get ahead of the outbreak with this pattern of transmission. Further exacerbated by the violence in the region, the control effort has major challenges that seem to be recognized, but the solutions are elusive. - Mod.LK]

- Wed 29 May 2019. Katwa: health worker
[Actualite, in French, machine trans., edited]
https://actualite.cd/2019/05/29/rdc-hostile-la-vaccination-un-agent-de-sante-meurt-debola-katwa
[byline: Christine Tshibuyi]

A health worker opposed to the vaccine against Ebola virus, which has affected the provinces of North-Kivu and Ituri for nearly 10 months, died of the virus on Mon [27 May 2019] in Katwa, North Kivu, the ministry of health said.

The unvaccinated (by refusal) health worker is among the 6 new confirmed cases and among the new community deaths reported on Tuesday evening [28 May 2019] by the ministry of health bulletin. "The cumulative number of confirmed/probable cases among health workers is 106 (5.5% of all confirmed/probable cases)," says the health authority in its bulletin.

Of these, 36 have already died. They are among the 1287 confirmed and probable cases that have died to date. The response to the Ebola outbreak is fraught with distrust and some kind of denial of disease by the people. They consider Ebola as a Western business, a strategy to exterminate them, or an act of witchcraft.

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail rapporteur Mary Marshall

[Maps of Congo DR: http://goo.gl/DM2AT8 and https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=6494013,194]

******
[4] Recommended reading
Date: Wed 29 May 2019
Source: New England Journal of Medicine [abridged, edited]
https://www.nejm.org/doi/full/10.1056/NEJMsr1904253


ref: Kale Ilunga Kalenga O, Moeti M, Sparrow A, et al. The ongoing Ebola epidemic in the Democratic Republic of Congo, 2018-2019. N Engl J Med. 2019 May 29. doi: 10.1056/NEJMsr1904253
---------------------------------------------------------------------
The authors conclude that "stopping this epidemic will require the alignment of the principal political and armed groups in eastern DRC in support of the response.

Conclusions. Global health and protection from global contagious threats rest on the public health capacity of each country. Even in the middle of intractable conflict, success in controlling Ebola must be achieved. We have the tools of global disease surveillance, rapid-response systems, and biomedical solutions -- if there is the political will to protect health workers in conflict zones while gaining the confidence of communities as primary partners in fighting outbreaks such as Ebola. Vigorous governmental leadership of the response must be balanced with attention to community concerns. The alignment of key political and armed groups behind the response effort is essential to stop the violence against health care and rehabilitate the humanitarian space required for outbreak control."

